[[Bach]], [[Beethoven]], [[Robert Schumann|Schumann]], [[Schubert]], [[Mozart]], [[Brahms]], [[Chopin]] and other classical and romantic composers.\n\nHer professionalism achieved worldwide recognition when a film (from 1999) was drawn to the attention of the press and went viral in 2013. At the start of a lunchtime concert in Amsterdam, she realised that she had rehearsed for a different Mozart concerto from the one the orchestra had started playing; quickly recovering, she played the concerto from memory.<ref>{{cite web|title=When Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires almost played the wrong piano concerto|url=http://www.classicfm.com/artists/maria-joao-pires/guides/wrong-piano-concerto/|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nPires performed at the [[BBC Proms]] in 2010. In an interview beforehand, she said that after 60 years of recitals and concerts she had cut back her performances but was non-committal about retirement.<ref name=Standard>{{cite news|publisher=London Evening Standard |date=21 July 2010 |title=Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires: I never said I would retire |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/maria-joo-pires-i-never-said-i-would-retire-6494364.html |accessdate=10 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518080456/http://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/maria-joo-pires-i-never-said-i-would-retire-6494364.html |archivedate=18 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2012 to 2016, she was a Master in Residence at the Queen Elisabeth Music Chapel in Waterloo, Belgium, where she gave piano lessons and [[master class]]es to young talented pianists from all over the world. To foster young musicians, she launched the Partitura Project.\n\nIn 2017, she announced her retirement from the stage and tours for 2018, but she continued giving concerts.<ref>[http://observador.pt/2017/12/18/maria-joao-pires-abandona-digressoes-mas-mantem-alguns-concertos-em-2018/ \"Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires abandona digress\u00f5es mas mant\u00e9m alguns concertos em 2018\"], [[Lusa News Agency]] via ''{{ill|Observador|pt|Observador (jornal)|lt=Observador}}'', 18 December 2017 {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20, 2019 she was awarded with a Doctorate Honorary Degree by [[Pompeu Fabra University]] of Barcelona.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upf.edu/web/universitat/maria-joao-pires|title=Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires, investida doctora honoris causa per la UPF - Sobre la Universitat Pompeu Fabra (UPF)|website=www.upf.edu|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nPires performs as a solo artist and in [[chamber music]]. Her many successful recordings include performances of the ''[[Moonlight sonata|Moonlight]]'' and other [[sonatas]] by Beethoven, ''Le Voyage Magnifique'' (the complete impromptus of Schubert), nocturnes and other works by Chopin, and Mozart trios with [[Augustin Dumay]] ([[violin]]) and [[Jian Wang (cellist)|Jian Wang]] ([[cello]]).\n\nShe won the [[Pessoa Prize]] in 1989, and founded the Belgais Centre for Study of the Arts in 1999.<ref name=Why>{{cite news|work=The Telegraph|date=12 April 2007|title=Why I turned my back on my homeland|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalmusic/3664431/Why-I-turned-my-back-on-my-homeland.html|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'' selected her recordings of the Chopin [[nocturne]]s as the best version available: \"I have no hesitation in declaring Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires&mdash;a pianist without a trace of narcissism&mdash;among the most eloquent master-musicians of our time.\" (Bryce Morrison).<ref>[http://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/chopin-nocturnes-4 Gramophone Recommended Recordings]</ref>\n\nAnother of her acclaimed recordings is ''Mozart: The Piano Sonatas''. According to the ''Penguin Guide'', \"Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires is a stylist and a fine Mozartian. She is always refined yet never wanting in classical feeling, and she has a vital imagination. She strikes an ideal balance between poise and expressive sensibility, conveying a sense of spontaneity in everything she does.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.operamusica.com/artist/maria-joao-pires/biography#biography|title=Opera Musica|website=www.operamusica.com|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n==Partial discography==\n\n* Chopin, Schubert, Mozart etc.: Complete Concerto Recordings on [[Deutsche Grammophon]] 2014\n* Chopin, Schubert, Mozart etc.: Complete Solo Recordings on Deutsche Grammophon 2014\n* Mozart: Lieder and Arias [Accompanist to Barbara Hendricks] [EMI]\n* Mozart: Piano Sonatas Complete (Denon)\n* Beethoven: Piano Concertos 3 & 4 (2014, Onyx Classics)\n* Mozart: Piano Concertos 14, 17, 21, & 26 (2013, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Schubert (2013, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Chopin (2008, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Beethoven: Piano Sonatas (2001, [[Erato Records|Erato]])\n* Schumann: Piano Concerto, Piano Quintet (2000, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Chopin: Piano Concertos 1 & 2 (1999, Erato)\n* Franck, Debussy: Violin Sonatas; Ravel: Berceuse; Habanera; Tzigane (1996, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Mozart: Piano Sonatas K. 281, K. 282, K. 533/K. 494 (1993, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Mozart: Piano Sonatas K. 331 & 457; Fantasias K. 397 & 475 (1990, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Schubert: Sonata; 6 Moments Musicaux; 2 Scherzi (1989, Deutsche Grammophon)\n* Mozart: The Great Concertos for Piano (1978, Erato)\n\n==Move to Brazil==\nIn 2006 she moved to [[Lauro de Freitas]]&mdash;a town near [[Salvador, Brazil]]&mdash;and continued performing. At the time of her move, she commented that she had suffered much adverse publicity in Portugal due to her Belgais Centre project to help tackle the significant problem of underprivileged children, a project that the Portuguese Government helped to fund but publicly shied away from.<ref>[http://www.publico.clix.pt/shownews.asp?id=1265457 Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires troca Belgais por nova vida no Brasil] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070505015655/http://www.publico.clix.pt/shownews.asp?id=1265457 |date=2007-05-05 }}, article in Portuguese in ''[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]''</ref> The centre continued to operate at her farm in Portugal<ref name=Why /> and she subsequently started similar projects in Brazil.<ref name=Standard />\n\nIn 2017, she moved back to Belgais, in Portugal.\n\n==Social engagement==\n\"It is in response to this issue that Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires launched the Partitura project. It is all about creating favourable circumstances for transmission by encouraging reciprocal listening between generations: inciting well-known musicians to foster young musicians and to invite them (as the name suggests) to share the concert platform\".<ref>[https://musicchapel.org/partitura-2/ Partitura Music Chape Maria Jo\u00e3o Pires]</ref>\n\n== Honours and Awards ==\n\n=== Honours ===\n\n* [[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Knight BAR.png|alt=|60x60px]] [[Dame]] of the [[Order of Saint James of the Sword]]  (9 August 1983)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=153|title=Cidad\u00e3os Nacionais Agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas|website=P\u00e1gina Oficial das Ordens Honor\u00edficas Portuguesas|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Commander BAR.png|alt=|60x60px]] [[Commander#Military and chivalric orders|Commander]] of the [[Order of Saint James of the Sword|Order of Prince Henry]] (9 June 1989)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\" />\n* [[File:PRT Order of Saint James of the Sword - Grand Cross BAR.svg|alt=|60x60px]] [[Grand Cross]] of the Order of Saint James of the Sword  (9 June 1998)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\" />\n* [[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Grand Cross BAR.png|alt=|60x60px]] Grand Cross of the Order of Prince Henry (19 May 2019)<ref name=\"OrdHonPor\" />\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n<references />\n\n'''Sources'''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100113125014/http://www.transartists.nl/air/belgais_centre_for_the_study_of_arts.7335.html Belgais Centre]\n*[http://www.deutschegrammophon.com/en/artist/pires/b